@node "issues" "Issues"
@{b}Issues@{ub}
------

There are a number of things to watch out for and be aware of when using this
program.

* The display physical size option does not produce
  results that concur with the system and or other
  counting programs that attempt this feature.

  For example I can count a number of files with
  the "list" command which come to 130 blocks * 512 bytes
  block size = 66560 bytes. If I count the same files with
  "AppiSizer" I get 67072 bytes physical size. If I count
  the same files again with "Count" I get 62976 bytes.

  The internals of the routine that works the physical size
  out are quite simple; multiply the block size of the disk
  containing the files by the number of blocks taken by
  each file. This should produce consistant results when
  compared with other programs but it does not. If anyone
  knows why this is, please get in contact with me so that
  I can fix it.

* If your directory tree is very very deep there is a chance
  that "Count" may crash due to insufficent stack space. I
  do not antisipate this actually happening as I give each
  counting thread 20k of stack. If this happens to you
  please contact me and I'll add an option to change the
  stack space.

* At the moment if you count files that total more than
  4 gigabytes, count's size will wrap around. Again I don't
  beleive this will be a problem, but if you dearly want
  to count *loads* and loads of huge files then contact
  me and I'll try to help.
@endnode

@node "useage" "Useage"
@{b}Useage@{ub}
------

In order to count the size of any workbench item (disk, drawer, file etc.)
just drop it onto the count icon which will appear on the workbench screen as
an AppIcon. This will open a window which will display all the information
about the file(s) dropped. No need to close this window in order to count
other items; its multithreaded! :-)

To quit count just double-click on this AppIcon.
@endnode

